<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="un1013k"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="un1" href="#un1013">UN1: </a>  <a href="../../FF/unbs/un1all.htm#un1013k"> (NLI.3) 13(k)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> sarga (path of outgoing)</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">True Will-power is surely the power and energy of the whole, as much on the physical plane and on the <mark>&ldquo;path of outgoing,&rdquo;</mark> as on the Buddhic plane and the &ldquo;path of return&rdquo;; it actually is that very rhythmical swing which makes those outward and returning paths&mdash;those <mark>sargas</mark> and pralayas&mdash;and that which is gained by the limited J&iuml;va by cultivation of Truth and Poise is surely a wider consciousness, a consciousness in which he has a sense of oneness with the organic whole, whose consciousness is this Will-power, accompanied by the knowledge that much that appears to his still limited consciousness has no real existence in the complete consciousness of that all-upholding One of which he is part. <small> <a name="THRdec1908" href="/udra/udex.htm#THRdec1908"><cite title="source">The Theosophical Review</cite></a> (December 1908), Unsigned, &ldquo;Queries and Notes. VII&rdquo; 369</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c07255k" href="../../../F/FF/fnbs/c07all.htm#c07255k">VI.C.07:255(k)</a> </dd> </dd></dl>
